@Psykes7  

Let's not get into the fact that despite the fact that the Maze was made by Azor I in the olden days of Ravnica, the Maze's End has pillars with the modern interpretations of the guild symbols.  

Regarding the card itself, I find it somewhat clunky even as a land-gathering mechanic. I wouldn't even call it flavorful since it doesn't detail any of the Who/What/When/Where/Whys without any flavor text. All in all, I'd use it mostly as a goofy way to get around an instant win, but there are certainly better and more efficient ways to win the game by card-text.

This card can be a win condition, sure, but has anyone considered using it as simply a slower [thawing glaciers](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=thawing glaciers)? I mean, a land that tutors lands from your library to the battlefield is kind of cool. Of course, adding a bunch of "come into play tapped lands" is a hefty penalty, but card advantage from a land deserves a second glance.  

Also, cards like [Hold the Gates](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Hold the Gates) and [Crackling Perimeter](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Crackling Perimeter) are all of a sudden no joke. 5/9 vigilance Thragtusk producing a 3/9 vigilance token upon death? Tap a land = deal 1 damage to each opponent? These pack some serious bang for the buck.  

@Mode: Well [Eye of Ugin](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Eye of Ugin) was actually the first Mythic Rare land. Apparently mythic rare lands like to tutor block thematic stuff.
